Estimates of species climate niches

Calculate species niche.

dat_niche <- calc_species_niche(dat_trait, add_dummy = T)

Plot the niche of an individual species.

gg_individual_trait_species_niche_cool <- plot_individual_trait_species_niche_ind_sp(dat_occ, dat_trait, sp = "Danthonia californica")
gg_individual_trait_species_niche_cool

Figure 1. Example species _Danthonia californica _distributions in geographical space and climate space. The left shows GBIF occurrence records in the CFP. The right panel shows the number of GBIF records (n) and their distribution in reference to mean annual temperature and precipitation from CHELSA data. The scatters are summarized by axis rugs for marginal distributions, as well as a Gaussian data ellipse at the 95% confidence interval and a centroid cross (median) for the joint distribution.

Plot the niche of all species.

gg_species_niche <- plot_species_niche(dat_niche,
  cool_species = "Danthonia californica",
  warm_species = "Stipa pulchra"
)
gg_species_niche

Figure 2. Grassland species occur along geographic and climatic gradients to estimate niches. Estimated climate optima from the medians of temperature and precipitation for each species (gray), highlighting the two species (blue and red).

Observational and experimental evidence of community shifts

Calculate CTI CPI in observations and experiments.

dat_index <- calc_community_index(dat_niche = dat_niche, dat_community = dat_community)

Plot changes in CTI and CPI.

gg_community_index_obs <- plot_community_index(option = "obs", dat_index = dat_index)
gg_community_index_obs

Figure 3. Grassland community shifts from long-term observations. Consistent with climate warming and drying, grassland communities shift dominance to species associated with warmer (increasing CTI) and drier (decreasing CPI) locations in 12 long-term observational sites across the California Floristic Province (red trend lines by linear regression, significant slopes by t-test, p \(\leq\) 0.05). The map shows the geographical distribution of the 12 sites with grassland percent cover (green) from Sentinel-2 10 m land use/land cover time series data. 

gg_community_index_exp <- plot_community_index(option = "exp", dat_index = dat_index, experiment = "jrgce", treatment = "warming")
gg_community_index_exp

Figure 4. Grassland community shifts from a long-term experiment. Warming treatment causes communities to shift dominance to species associated with warmer (CTI) and drier (CPI) locations in the Jasper Ridge Global Change Experiment (72 ambient plots in black, 64 warming plots in red, effect in each year estimated with linear regression, t-test, ns: p \(\gt\) 0.05, \(*\): p \(\leq\) 0.05, \(**\): p \(\leq\) 0.01, \(***\): p \(\leq\) 0.001). The orange background shades denote phase I (+80 W m-2 heating) in 1999-2002, phase II (+100 W m-2 heating) in 2003-2009, and phase III (+250 W m-2 heating) in 2010-2014.

Analysis and synthesis of community shifts

Analyze species contributing to CTI CPI change.

dat_gainloss <- calc_species_gainloss(dat_community = dat_community, dat_niche = dat_niche)
gg_species_gainloss <- plot_species_gainloss(dat_niche = dat_niche, dat_gainloss = dat_gainloss)
#> [1] FALSE
#> [1] FALSE
gg_species_gainloss$obs$circle_detail

Figure 5. Changes in species abundance during grassland community compositional shifts at the observational sites. Climate niches of species with a significant increase in abundance over time (green circle), with a significant decrease in abundance over time (orange circle), established (green-filled circle), extirpated (orange-filled circle), and all other species present at each observational site (gray circle) (t-test, p \(\gt\) 0.05). The size of the circles is proportional to the species’ dominance in the community, showing no clear pattern of either a few dominant species or many rare species driving the community compositional shift. Abbreviated names of species recruited and extirpated were labeled. 

gg_species_gainloss$exp$circle_detail

Figure 6. Changes in species abundance during grassland community compositional shifts in experiments. Climate niches of species with a significant increase in abundance under warming (green circle), with a significant decrease in abundance under warming (orange circle), and all other species present in each year of three phases of the Jasper Ridge Global Change Experiment (gray) (t-test, p \(\gt\) 0.05). The size of the circles is proportional to the species’ dominance in the community, showing no clear pattern of either a few dominant species or many rare species driving the community compositional shift. Abbreviated names of species significantly increased or decreased in abundance were labeled.
